<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><rss xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" version="2.0" xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/"><channel><title><![CDATA[Realistic dreameR]]></title><description><![CDATA[Googling can make everything possible!]]></description><link>https://www.nadaegyun.com/</link><image><url>https://www.nadaegyun.com/favicon.png</url><title>Realistic dreameR</title><link>https://www.nadaegyun.com/</link></image><generator>Jamify 1.0</generator><lastBuildDate>Fri, 07 May 2021 07:32:51 GMT</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://www.nadaegyun.com/rss/" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><ttl>60</ttl><item><title><![CDATA[How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi]]></title><description><![CDATA[Raspberry Pi can be set up without monitor and keyboard as headless setup and how to set up Raspberry Pi without monitor and keyboard will be introduced as 5 steps.]]></description><link>https://www.nadaegyun.com/headless-raspberry-pi</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Ghost__Post__60922d4792c5af001c53bfbf</guid><category><![CDATA[RaspberryPi]]></category><dc:creator><![CDATA[Daegyun Na]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 06 May 2021 06:19:00 GMT</pubDate><media:content url="https://www.nadaegyun.com/static/4bd69d98a8fedf959376ae607f97df98/photo-1552283576-3ea3519bf12e.jpg" medium="image"/><content:encoded><![CDATA[<blockquote>Raspberry Pi can be set up without monitor and keyboard as headless setup and how to set up Raspberry Pi without monitor and keyboard will be introduced as 5 steps.</blockquote><h2 id="install-raspberry-pi-os">Install Raspberry Pi OS</h2><img src="https://www.nadaegyun.com/static/4bd69d98a8fedf959376ae607f97df98/photo-1552283576-3ea3519bf12e.jpg" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/><p>You can install Raspberry Pi OS on microSD card, USB memory stick or USB external storage such as SSD/HDD that you need to update firmware.</p><h3 id="install-raspberry-pi-imager">Install Raspberry Pi Imager</h3><p>Install <a href="https://www.raspberrypi.org/software/">Raspberry Pi Imager </a>from <a href="https://www.raspberrypi.org/software/">www.raspberrypi.org</a></p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-5.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-3.38.37-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><h3 id="install-raspberry-pi-os-1">Install Raspberry Pi OS</h3><p>Run Raspberry Pi Imager and choose OS. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-1.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-3.45.03-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>You can choose several OS and recommend Raspberry Pi OS (32-bit)</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-3.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-3.31.47-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Click CHOOSE STORAGE</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-4.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-3.31.54-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Select your storage from the menu</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-2.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-3.32.21-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Then click WRITE. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-3.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-3.51.04-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>This takes several minutes as Raspberry Pi Imager downloads and burns selected Raspberry Pi OS to selected storage.</p><p>Writing</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-1.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-3.32.51-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Verifying</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-4.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-3.35.38-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Completed</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-5.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-3.35.54-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><h2 id="set-up-ssh">Set up SSH</h2><p>SSH (Secure Socket Shell) is required to enable before you insert the storage you installed Raspberry Pi OS into your Raspberry Pi. </p><p>Open the boot folder of the installed storage</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-3.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-4.52.18-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Create a file named "ssh" which is empty and no file extension in the boot folder</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-5.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-4.53.03-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>If Raspberry Pi is connected to your network via wired connection, you don't need to set up Wi-Fi and go to SSH connection to Raspberry Pi to enable VNC.</p><h2 id="set-up-wi-fi">Set up Wi-Fi</h2><p>To set up a Wi-Fi connection on your Raspberry Pi you need to put wpa_supplicant.conf with following text in the boot folder you created "ssh" file. </p><div class="kg-card kg-code-card gatsby-highlight" data-language="text"><pre class="language-text"><code class="language-text">ctrl_interface=DIR=/var/run/wpa_supplicant GROUP=netdev
update_config=1
country=&#x3C;Insert 2 letter ISO 3166-1 country code here>

network={
 ssid="&#x3C;Name of your wireless LAN>"
 psk="&#x3C;Password for your wireless LAN>"
}</code></pre></div><p>Please refer to following example</p><div class="kg-card kg-code-card gatsby-highlight" data-language="text"><pre class="language-text"><code class="language-text">ctrl_interface=DIR=/var/run/wpa_supplicant GROUP=netdev
update_config=1
country=&#x3C;Insert 2 letter ISO 3166-1 country code here>

network={
 ssid="nadaegyun"
 psk="iloveyou"
}</code></pre></div><p>When Raspberry Pi first boots, it will copy that file into the correct location in the Linux root file system and use those settings to start up Wi-Fi.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-4.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-5.16.53-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>After Raspberry Pi is connected to power, make sure to wait a few minutes for it to boot up and register on the network.</p><h2 id="getting-raspberry-pi-ip-address">Getting Raspberry Pi IP address</h2><p>To connect to your Raspberry Pi using SSH to enable VNC you need to know the IP address of your Raspberry Pi. This is easy if you have a monitor.</p><h3 id="get-the-ip-address-from-your-router">Get the IP address from your router</h3><p>You can check all IP addressses from the main menu of your router, probably visit to http://192.168.1.1 and check IP address. </p><p>Here is an example how I got the IP address of my Raspberry Pi.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-5.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-11.15.11-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><h3 id="resolving-raspberrypi-local-with-mdns">Resolving raspberrypi.local with mDNS</h3><p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multicast_DNS"/><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avahi_%28software%29">Y</a>ou can reach your Raspberry Pi by using its hostname.local and ping will show its IP address if it is reachable.</p><div class="kg-card kg-code-card gatsby-highlight" data-language="text"><pre class="language-text"><code class="language-text">ping raspberrypi.local</code></pre></div><div class="kg-card kg-code-card gatsby-highlight" data-language="text"><pre class="language-text"><code class="language-text">PING raspberrypi.local (192.168.1.99): 56 data bytes
64 bytes from 192.168.1.131: icmp_seq=0 ttl=255 time=2.618 ms</code></pre></div><h3 id="nmap-command">nmap command</h3><p>To use <code class="language-text">nmap</code> to scan the devices on your network, you need to know the subnet you are connected to. First find your own IP address, in other words the one of the computer you're using to find your Pi's IP address:</p><div class="kg-card kg-code-card gatsby-highlight" data-language="bash"><pre class="language-bash"><code class="language-bash">nmap -sn <span class="token number">192.168</span>.1.0/24</code></pre></div><p>Ping scan just pings all the IP addresses to see if they respond. For each device that responds to the ping, the output shows the hostname and IP address like so:</p><div class="kg-card kg-code-card gatsby-highlight" data-language="text"><pre class="language-text"><code class="language-text">Starting Nmap 6.40 ( http://nmap.org ) at 2014-03-10 12:46 GMT
Nmap scan report for hpprinter (192.168.1.2)
Host is up (0.00044s latency).
Nmap scan report for Gordons-MBP (192.168.1.4)
Host is up (0.0010s latency).
Nmap scan report for ubuntu (192.168.1.5)
Host is up (0.0010s latency).
Nmap scan report for raspberrypi (192.168.1.8)
Host is up (0.0030s latency).
Nmap done: 256 IP addresses (4 hosts up) scanned in 2.41 seconds</code></pre></div><h3 id="getting-the-ip-address-of-a-pi-using-your-smartphone">Getting the IP address of a Pi using your smartphone</h3><p>The Fing app is a free network scanner for smartphones. It is available for <a href="https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.overlook.android.fing">Android</a> and <a href="https://itunes.apple.com/gb/app/fing-network-scanner/id430921107?mt=8">iOS</a>.</p><p>Your phone and your Raspberry Pi have to be on the same network, so connect your phone to the correct wireless network.</p><p>When you open the Fing app, touch the refresh button in the upper right-hand corner of the screen. After a few seconds you will get a list with all the devices connected to your network. Scroll down to the entry with the manufacturer "Raspberry Pi". You will see the IP address in the bottom left-hand corner, and the MAC address in the bottom right-hand corner of the entry.</p><h2 id="ssh-connection-to-raspberry-to-enable-vnc">SSH connection to Raspberry to enable VNC</h2><p>Now you can connect to your Raspberry Pi using SSH with the IP address of your Raspberry Pi in terminal.</p><div class="kg-card kg-code-card gatsby-highlight" data-language="bash"><pre class="language-bash"><code class="language-bash"><span class="token function">ssh</span> pi@your Raspberry Pi IP address</code></pre></div><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-5.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.14.59-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Enter "raspberry" as default password</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-3.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.31.24-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>then your Raspberry Pi is connected by using SSH</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-2.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.15.29-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><h2 id="other-configuration-for-headless-raspberry-pi">Other configuration for headless Raspberry Pi</h2><p>After SSH is connected to your Raspberry, some more configuration is required in raspi-config.</p><ul><li>Configuration tool update</li><li>Desktop auto login</li><li>Enable VNC</li><li>Virtual desktop display</li><li>Bootloader update for external USB storage</li></ul><p>First, enter 'sudo raspi-config' in termal.</p><div class="kg-card kg-code-card gatsby-highlight" data-language="bash"><pre class="language-bash"><code class="language-bash"><span class="token function">sudo</span> raspi-config</code></pre></div><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-3.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.15.43-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Then you will see the main menu of Raspberry Pi software configuraiton Tool</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-4.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-11.21.21-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><h3 id="configuration-tool-update">Configuration tool update</h3><p>First select 8 Update </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-5.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-11.27.07-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>You will see update progress as below</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-2.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.15.55-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><h3 id="desktop-auto-login">Desktop auto login</h3><p>select 1 System Option</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-4.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-11.21.21-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>S5 Boot / Auto Login</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-5.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-11.28.42-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>B4 Desktop Autologin Desktop GUI</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-5.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-11.23.46-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><h3 id="enable-vnc">Enable VNC</h3><p>This will be enable VNC so that you can connect your Raspberry without Monitor with <a href="https://www.realvnc.com/en/connect/download/viewer/">RealVNC viewer</a>.</p><p>Select 3 Interface Options</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-5.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-11.29.16-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Select P3 VNC</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-1.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-5.50.44-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Select Yes to enable VNC</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-3.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-5.51.03-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Now VNC is enable.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-4.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-5.56.35-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><h2 id="virtual-desktop-display">Virtual desktop display</h2><p>To set up headless Raspberry Pi you need to use virtual desktop and enable HDMI with some resolution. Otherwise you will see black screen when you connect to your Raspberry Pi with VNC as below.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-4.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-6.08.26-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Select 6 Advanced Options</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-4.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.17.33-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Select A8 HDMI / Composite</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-1.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.18.21-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Select V1 Enable 4kp60 HDMI</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-1.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.18.25-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>After HDMI is enable then set resolution. Select 2 Display Options</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-1.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.58.30-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Select D1 Resolution</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-2.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.58.47-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Select DMT Mode 82 as recommendation</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-4.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.59.24-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><h2 id="boot-loader-update-for-external-usb-storage">Boot loader update for external USB storage</h2><p>If you don't use external USB storage, you don't need to.</p><p>Select 6 Advanced Options</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-4.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.17.33-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Select A7 Bootloader Version</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-4.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.17.44-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Select E1 Latest version boot ROM software</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-4.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.17.49-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Latest version boot ROM will be loaded at next reboot.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-3.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.17.52-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Boot order also can be chosen in 6 Advanced Options</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-3.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-4.09.53-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Select A6 Boot Order</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-4.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-4.09.22-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>You can choose your setting</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-3.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-4.09.37-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Select &#x3C;Finish> to apply changes</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-1.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.18.36-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Select &#x3C;Yes> to reboot.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-5.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.18.39-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p/><h2 id="connect-to-raspberry-pi-using-vnc">Connect to Raspberry Pi using VNC</h2><p>Install <a href="https://www.realvnc.com/en/connect/download/viewer/">Realvnc viewer</a> and enter 'your Raspberry IP address'</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-4.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.18.58-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Connecting to your Raspberry</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-5.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.19.05-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Click Continue</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-2.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-11.38.47-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Enter 'pi' and 'raspberry' as default</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-5.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-05-at-11.39.09-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Finally headless Raspberry Pi has been completed if you see the following.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-2.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.20.04-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Now you can change resolution as you want. Click Raspberry Pi icon on the left of top and go preferences and Screen configuration.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-2.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.22.44-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Click Configure, Screens, HDMI-1 and Resolution.Choose your favorite resolution and apply.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-1.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.23.06-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>Headless Raspberry Pi setting is completed.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://res-2.cloudinary.com/hrvj5zvjc/image/upload/q_auto/v1/ghost-blog-images/Screen-Shot-2021-05-07-at-3.23.20-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to set up Headless Raspberry Pi"/></figure><p>I will add video clip for better understanding later.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Adobe illustrator - Part I]]></title><description><![CDATA[> The biggest difference between photoshop and illustrator is image format.
